Super cute restaurant and decor, best seating is by the windows, it gets a bit dark as you get further back.  Just a quick note - the menu online is not accurate/updated.  They offer happy hour everyday from 4-7pm with $5 small plates and specials on beer/wine/cocktails.  So we liked this since it was a Saturday!  Brunch is served on Sat/Sun from 10a-3p.  STARTER: We started out with the HH roasted calamari which had a nice Mediterranean twist with capers, sun dried tomatoes, shallots served in a broth with crusty bread.  Highly recommend as a starter and the calamari was cooked perfectly, not chewy at all.  ENTREES: Crab Cake Sandwich ($18) with jumbo lump crab, lettuce tomato, old bay aioli and fries. *Really delicious blue crab meat, very little filler, only complaint was that the crab cake itself wasn't a bit larger.  The fries were surprisingly soggy!  Not sure if they were having an off day, but maybe go with a different side.  Haddock Picatta ($21) served with brown rice and sauteed spinach. *I opted no Picatta sauce and honestly the fish was so delicious by itself, I didn't need the sauce.  The haddock was a fresh and healthy 8 oz-ish portion served over a bed of tasty brown rice with scallions and a huge portion of sauteed spinach.  I found the spinach to be a little too salty and wilted for me but it went well with the rice.  SERVICE: Our server was attentive and came by as needed, no complaints there.  I would definitely be interested in coming back for brunch on the weekend and checking out their desserts.

Our server took 15 minutes to get 4 waters, 2 juices and 2 beers (which she spilled 1 and 2 waters and had to return for more) the beers weren't even brought in the bottles, just poured into a glass, so who knows what we actually got. The food, was hot when it arrived, except for the bacon that I ordered with the pancakes (that was a soggy cold addition). The crab cake, was at best a 2 oz. patty on a massive sized bun (in comparison). Look, I get that crab is expensive, but to serve that, that was just cheap! It all smacked of the attitude that "we can do whatever we want bc it's DC". I didn't not tip the server, but I definitely didn't tip what a decent service - meal would have required. I can honestly say that I will never go back, too many other places to go try.

We've ordered the grilled salmon and the Chesapeake stuffed flounder. Both dishes were excellent, cooked perfectly. The presentation and the sides complimented the fish extremely well.  Before Ophelia's we would  go to Matchbox for the salmon and halibut and the dishes we had from Ophelia's were definitely much better. I would say the style is simple, very flavorful, and very well designed dishes from people who know what they are doing.  It doesn't seem as much thought is out into the matchbox dishes. By far our new favorite restaurant in Capitol Hill.
